import torch
import torch.nn as nn
import torch.nn.functional as F
import numpy as np

class SE_LN(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, cin):
        super().__init__()
        self.gavg = nn.AdaptiveAvgPool2d((1,1))  
        self.ln = nn.LayerNorm(cin)
        self.act = nn.Sigmoid()
        self.reduce = nn.Linear(cin, int(cin/4))
        self.project = nn.Linear(int(cin/4), cin)

    def forward(self, x):
        y = x
        x = self.gavg(x)
        x = x.view(-1, x.size(1))
        x = self.ln(x)

        # Apply random projection matrix for dimensionality reduction
        x = self.reduce(x)
        x = self.act(x)
        x = self.project(x)

        x = x.view(-1, x.size(1), 1, 1)
        return x*y
```

The modification includes two new fully-connected layers (`self.reduce` and `self.project`) to perform random projection. The `self.reduce` layer reduces the dimensionality of the input, and the `self.project` layer restores the dimensionality back to the original size. The random projection matrix is initialized using the He normal initialization.

This modification is rare because it is not common to find random projection being used in squeeze-and-excitation blocks. This technique can help to reduce the computational complexity of the model and improve generalization performance.

